<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-921-746  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 921 746.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 12 1989 n1185 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>BMA slams hospitals' trial network. (the British MedicalAssociation finds six UK resource management initiative pilotsites deficient)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Haughton, Emma.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A report of the British Medical Association's (BMA) evaluation ofthe six pilot hospital sites of the UK government's resourcemanagement initiative (RMI) to enable hospitals to 'opt out' ofthe National Health Service (NHS) condemns the tightimplementation time scales, tight budgets, and staff shortages.andO;None of the six hospitals are ready to recommend the RMI program,which would spend 260 million pounds sterling to providecentralized computer facilities to enable 260 large UK generalhospitals to monitor and control treatment costs and resources.andO;BMA believes that there is no conclusive evidence indicating thatimproved patient care will result from the RMI program.andO;Additional reports from the National Health Service and from BMAare due Nov 1989.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     British Medical AssociationHospital Information SystemsPilot ProjectsUnited Kingdom.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>